{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480646"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"89"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"89","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/89"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.04,0.1,0.07,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"89"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107296"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"89","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/89"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"89"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89758"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"164"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39498"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41985"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107296"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe left-sided headache. He describes a two-week history of recurrent left-sided retro-orbital pain occurring three to five times daily, lasting 15-30 minutes per episode. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with a pain score of 10/10. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is marked conjunctival injection and lacrimation of the left eye with ipsilateral rhinorrhoea. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal. He has been commenced on high-flow 100% oxygen via non-rebreather mask but continues to experience severe pain after 20 minutes of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subcutaneous sumatriptan","Oral caffeine","Intranasal lignocaine","Intravenous fentanyl","Oral verapamil"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of cluster headache: strictly unilateral severe pain with ipsilateral autonomic features (conjunctival injection, lacrimation, rhinorrhoea) occurring in a predictable pattern multiple times per day. High-flow 100% oxygen has been trialled but has not provided adequate relief after 20 minutes, indicating the need for additional acute treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous sumatriptan\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step, with onset within 15 minutes in most patients. It has the strongest evidence base among acute treatments for cluster headache and is considered first-line therapy alongside high-flow oxygen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral caffeine\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in treating cluster headaches. While it may help post-lumbar puncture headaches by stimulating cerebrospinal fluid production, it is ineffective for cluster headaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntranasal lignocaine\u003C/strong\u003E has limited efficacy, helping only about one-third of patients. It could be considered as an adjunct if first-line treatments are ineffective or contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fentanyl\u003C/strong\u003E, while effective for severe pain, carries unnecessary risks of sedation and respiratory depression when safer and equally effective alternatives exist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral verapamil\u003C/strong\u003E is an important preventive medication for cluster headache but has no role in acute attack management. When used prophylactically, regular ECG monitoring is required due to the risk of heart block at the high doses often needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh-flow 100% oxygen via non-rebreather mask for 15-20 minutes is effective in about two-thirds of patients and has an excellent safety profile. When oxygen therapy fails to provide adequate relief, as in this case, subcutaneous sumatriptan becomes the next most appropriate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subcutaneous sumatriptan is the first-line treatment for an acute cluster headache attack.","100% oxygen is a very effective and generally safe treatment for acute cluster headaches and should be considered in an emergency department presentation.","Cluster headaches typically present with strictly unilateral pain, autonomic features, and predictable timing of attacks."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Neurology: Cluster headache. In: Therapeutic Guidelines: Neurology. Version 3. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2017. Available at: https://app.tg.org.au.acs.hcn.com.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Neurology\u0026topicfile=cluster-headache\u0026guidelinename=Neurology\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e60#toc_d1e60"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89758"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"89"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89758","link